@node P1 "Editor's Corner"
@toc "menu"

Editor's Corner             by @{"Lori Vinciguerra" link P6}

The "Schools with Amigas" list has reached 100 with the addition of two new
schools this quarter.  Unfortunately we have lost the Orange Coast College
in Costa Mesa, California from our list.  John Hanna informed me that the
decision to get rid of the Amigas was based on many factors, including the
lack of hardware and software vendor support.  They have decided to buy
Macs and may even add some UNIX workstations to their graphics program.  I
am particularly aware of the hesitant attitudes of US vendors and dealers
to jump back into the Amiga market.  It seems to me that the vendors who
stayed involved are definately devoted and provide excellent support.
However, even some of the new Amiga retail stores are not carrying much
inventory. Their reply to requests from potential customers is that Amigans
buy primarily from mail order.  Everyone who is interested in having good
local support from the dealers should be visiting their stores even if it
is just to browse.  The dealers need to know that when we want to buy
something or have something repaired we will support the local retail shop.

Other evidence of vendor uneasiness is the delay of AC's Guide which was
due to come out first in the fall and then in winter.  The delay, as I
understand it, is due to the lack of content for the publication.  I agree
that it would look bad to put out a very thin issue of the Guide.  However,
this delay is making current and future Amiga customers feel like things
are still up in the air.  Hopefully, the delay will be resolved soon.

Since the last issue of the AEL newsletter, the World Wide Web has really
taken off.  In this issue, look for Ralph Vinciguerra's article on
preparing material for the Web. Also, check out OWL's Web site (address
listed in article).  We have links to some of the cool places that an
Amigan would want to travel. Access to this newsletter will be added to the
Web site soon.

We will be cutting down on the number of paper copies of the newsletter
that are sent by US mail.  If you are still interested in receiving it by
US mail, please send me a quick note.  I am hoping that most people will be
able to receive it electronically.  The duplication and mailing costs (and
the time it took to format it) were just getting to be too much.

The deadline for article submissions for the summer issue is June 1,
1996.  Articles about anything that you are doing with your Amiga that
is related to education would be great. As always, email your article to
owl@davinci.reading.ma.us or use U.S. mail to send to OWL Software, 460
Summer Ave., Reading, MA 01867-3819.


